	Date: Sun 6 Dec 87 12:35:19-PST
	From: David Roode &lt;ROODE@BIONET-20.ARPA&gt;
	Subject: MX records

	But perhaps people don't realize that the UU.NET domain service
	for UUCP simply fabricates an MX record for each and every
	x.UU.NET query given it.

I think you are confusing "UUNET" with "UUCP".  UUNET is just one
of several companies that provide UUCP for a fee. The only machines
registered within the domain ".UU.NET" are the actual service
machines (mail relays).  The organizations that are members of UUNET
register in the top-level domain that is more appropriate for them,
such as .EDU or .COM. The relaying is done by UUNET only for a small
subset of the registered UUCP domains.  Many of them relay through
machines much closer to them.  For example, "Adobe.COM" is registered
in the UUCP zone, but relays through Sun.COM since it is just down
the street from us.

Similarly, each BITNET site should be registered in .EDU or .COM, with
MX records pointing to nearby relaying sites, instead of having a
single relay like WISCVM.  This is already being done slowly, starting
with sites that are on the Internet: witness CUNYVM.CUNY.EDU,
Forsythe.Stanford.EDU, etc.

	-- WIN

